Politics, it's like a distant noise, you know? It's always on TV, but what can you do about it? I have my daily worries, getting by with the rent and food for my family. I don't see how voting or joining parties will help me pay the bills. My husband's been laid off from the factory again, and I'm working double shifts to make ends meet. Politicians just promise and promise but nothing changes for people like us.

My niece's son is studying politics in school now, but he says it's all just theory and useless if you don't have connections or money. My cousin got involved with one of those groups that promise to fight for workers' rights, but she got tired of arguing and quit. It's hard to get worked up about something when there are more pressing problems.

I do remember the good old days, when Eva Perón was in power, and it seemed like things were better for a while. But times changed, and now I don't know who to trust or what's the point of getting involved.

profile_1774_llama3.1:8b.think_process:
To be honest, I'm not really into politics. I have a job and a family to take care of, so I don't have the time or energy to get too caught up in it. My grandmother always used to say that we should just let the politicians handle things because they're smart and will make decisions for us. I trust them to do what's best for our country. Besides, politics seems complicated and confusing - I like thinking about simple things like raising my kids and making a good life for myself.

I know some people are really passionate about it, but I'm not one of those people. My husband is more into that sort of thing, he always has the TV on during election times, so I get updates from him. That's nice, but it's not something I really engage with myself. Politics seems like a distant thing to me, far removed from my daily life.

I do care about some issues, like education for our kids and healthcare for everyone, because they directly affect us. But politics is such a big picture thing - what's the point of getting too worked up about it? I'm happy just living my life and taking things as they come. If someone else wants to get involved in politics, that's their choice, but it's not mine.

profile_1971_llama3.1:8b.think_process: Politics? Me? I don't know if I really care about it. My mom always says that as long as the economy is doing well and there's food on the table, that's all we need to worry about. And most of my friends feel the same way. They're not interested in politics because they think it doesn't affect them directly. But sometimes I see these protests and marches on TV and it makes me think maybe we should be paying attention. My tío was involved with the union at his factory and he said that things would get worse if people didn't speak up. But honestly, most of the time politics seems like a bunch of old men talking about stuff that doesn't matter to us young people.

profile_1972_llama3.1:8b.think_process:
Politicians are always talking about things that don't matter to me. They promise one thing and do another. I'm too busy with my work and taking care of my family to worry about politics. My husband used to be into it, but he got tired of the arguing and just doesn't care anymore either.

My sister-in-law's cousin is a politician here in Buenos Aires and I know she thinks she knows what's best for everyone. But sometimes I see her making decisions that don't help my neighbors at all. And don't even get me started on the prices they charge for gas. It's like they're just trying to make things harder for us regular people.

My friend works at a shop near the Plaza de Mayo and she says the politicians are always talking about jobs and the economy, but nothing ever seems to change. My brother-in-law lost his job last year and it's been tough for him to find something new. So I think politics is just a bunch of talk and no action.

profile_1977_llama3.1:8b.think_process:
I'm not really sure why people always make such a big deal about politics. I mean, it's just the same old thing every time - politicians making promises they can't keep and blaming everyone else for their own mistakes. My brother-in-law says he's very interested in politics because he thinks it'll make him look smart to his friends, but I think he's just full of hot air. To me, politics is like watching the river flow by - it's always changing, but it's not really affecting my daily life. Unless something affects my family directly, I don't see why I should bother with all that.

My wife always says we need to get involved because our country needs people like us to make a change, but what can I do? I've got my job at the factory, and I'm lucky to have that. My time is better spent working or taking care of my family than worrying about some stuff that's not going to affect me directly. Besides, there's enough politics in my everyday life - on TV, with friends, even at work sometimes. Sometimes I feel like politicians are just pretending to listen and making up promises they don't intend to keep.

Politics seems like a hassle. My friends at the club are all about the latest football matches and who's dating who, not what's going on in politics. Besides, it's not like anyone actually cares about changing things around here - we've got our good lives and our nice families. I'll just stick to what I know and leave the politics to my parents.

But lately, there's been a lot of talk about inflation and how it's affecting our economy... that worries me a bit.

profile_2006_llama3.1:8b.think_process: I'm not sure I have much time for politics to be honest. I've got my family to think about, my work as an electrician, and my own little patch of land in the outskirts of Buenos Aires where I like to spend my free time. But you know, I do care about what's happening in Argentina, especially when it comes to the economy and how that affects my pocketbook. I'm worried about prices going up, inflation, and all those sorts of things. I don't have much faith in the politicians, they seem more interested in lining their own pockets than helping people like me. Still, I think someone's got to keep an eye on them, you know? Maybe if I stay informed, I can get a sense of what's going on and make some sort of difference.
